## Example 4 — Spinner Probability

### Step 1: Determine Favorable and Total Outcomes

**Problems 15–19:** Use the spinner to find each probability. If the spinner lands on a line, spin again.

[P(\text{red}) = \frac{\text{red sections}}{\text{total sections}}]
[P(\text{blue}) = \frac{\text{blue sections}}{\text{total sections}}]
[P(\text{green}) = \frac{\text{green sections}}{\text{total sections}}]
[P(\text{green or blue}) = P(\text{green}) + P(\text{blue})]
[P(\text{neither red nor yellow}) = 1 - P(\text{red}) - P(\text{yellow})]

## Example 5 — Assumptions in Geometric Probability

### Step 1: State Assumptions and Calculate

**Problem 20:** Deangelo waits for the Crimson bus (every 8 minutes) or Gold bus (every 15 minutes) with a 5-minute maximum wait.

**a.** Assumption: Buses arrive at consistent intervals and passengers arrive randomly.

**b.** Probability of waiting 5 minutes or less for both buses.
[P(\text{Crimson} \leq 5) = \frac{5}{8} = 0.625]
[P(\text{Gold} \leq 5) = \frac{5}{15} = 0.333]
Assuming independence: [P(\text{both}) = 0.625 \times 0.333 \approx 0.208 = 20.8\%]

**c.** Probability of waiting 5 minutes or less for only one bus.
[0.625 \times (1 - 0.333) + (1 - 0.625) \times 0.333 \approx 0.417 + 0.125 = 0.542 = 54.2\%]

